  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM refers to the anxiety and stress that individuals experience when they fear their performance might confirm negative stereotypes about their group. For me, as a retired transgender woman who grew up in a small Italian town and attended vocational school, I've witnessed how this phenomenon can silently undermine potential. My parents' educational backgrounds—my mother finishing lower secondary and my father upper secondary—shaped my early understanding of learning, but I never felt the same pressure to conform to gender roles that many others do. In STEM fields, where women and minorities are often underrepresented, stereotype threat manifests as self-doubt, reduced concentration, and even avoidance of participation. This isn't just a theoretical concern; it's a lived reality for many. I believe we must address it head-on, not through tokenism but through systemic change. Schools and workplaces should implement inclusive curricula that highlight diverse contributions to STEM, and mentorship programs that pair students with role models who share similar backgrounds. It’s crucial to foster environments where everyone feels safe to explore without fear of judgment. As someone who has spent time reading novels and painting, I know creativity and critical thinking are not confined to any one group. By dismantling stereotypes, we open doors for more voices to be heard and valued. In Lecce, where the sea and nature inspire so much, we can find parallels in how community and respect help us thrive. Addressing stereotype threat isn't just about fairness—it’s about nurturing the full potential of every individual, regardless of gender, background, or identity.",
